{
  "text": "The Pragmatic Engineer newsletter describes a 'product-minded' engineer as someone with developed product-thinking skills, a trend increasingly amplified by AI. This type of engineer actively cultivates their skills by consistently asking 'why,' using scenarios, engaging directly with customer support, and proactively assisting Product Managers with use cases. They also seek direct user insights by joining customer calls and leverage AI tools to aggregate user signals from various communication platforms. This product-mindedness extends to meticulously designing technical components, such as error messages, to serve as a primary product interface. These diagnostics are crafted for two distinct audiences: human users, who need contextual and actionable messages, and programmers/AI agents, who require typed errors with metadata for automated recovery. The goal is to provide diagnostics as early as possible in the workflow ('shifting left') to prevent deeper issues.\n\nThis differs from a stereotypical implementation-focused engineer, by implication, in that the product-minded engineer goes beyond simply building. While the evidence doesn't explicitly define the 'stereotypical implementation-focused engineer,' the contrast suggests that such an engineer might primarily focus on the technical execution of a task without the same emphasis on understanding the 'why' behind it, direct user empathy, proactive engagement with customer support or product management, or considering how even technical details like error messages function as part of the overall product experience for end-users and other systems. The product-minded engineer's focus is on the impact and usability of their work from a broader product perspective, actively seeking to align with user needs and business outcomes, rather than solely on the technical implementation details.",
  "cited_node_ids": [
    "nl-the-pragmatic-engineer-t"
  ],
  "citations": [
